<br>
Errors here surrounded by [EDIT] signs. No mistakes identified until second section entitled:<br>
<br>
The New Source of Energy<br>
<br>
The 1960's dawned in what appeared to be a nuclear century. Technology refined over the past two decades stood ready to change the world, for better or for worse. Reactors were being built, research expanding, and weapons being spawned of unimaginable power. When NASA set down the guidelines of the EMPIRE studies, it mandated the use of nuclear propulsion, a technology then in its infancy.<br>
<br>
It was only natural to eventually turn to nuclear power to leave the Earth. Like many advanced technologies, some of the first studies on nuclear rocketry were performed by the Germans. In 1942, German scientist Krafft A. Ehricke looked negatively upon the idea of nuclear rockets (4). Ironically when NASA asked General Dynamics/Astronautics to do a study on nuclear powered missions to Venus and Mars, Ehricke lead the study as head of their Advanced Studies Office. He would later do work on the ORION study as well. Nuclear rockets were no longer a thing to be looked down upon; they were seen as the future. <br>
<br>
Project EMPIRE focused on the use of solid core nuclear thermal rockets for propelling its interplanetary cruisers. The basic principles of rocket propulsion are the same for all propulsion systems. The nuclear rockets developed under early programs, such as KIWI and Rover, used a nuclear pile, similar to the core of a nuclear reactor, to heat a liquid propellant to extreme temperatures and expel the energized matter out the rocket's nozzle. Nuclear thermal rockets achieve much greater exhaust velocities, an important measure of efficiency,   <br>
<br>
[EDIT]   &quot;then&quot; - than  [EDIT]   chemical rockets. They also achieved much higher specific impulse, or Isp, a rating of the thrust gained in one second from one unit mass of propellant. Nuclear rockets of the day reached Isp's of 800-900s, with thrust to weight ratios greater than one. In addition to space-based nuclear rockets, NASA's NERVA (Nuclear Engine for Rocket Vehicle Application) program planned to apply them to booster technology, particularly the upper stage of a modified Saturn V, the Saturn V/N.<br>
<br>
The men who thought up ORION did not make rockets, they built bombs. ORION was based   <br>
<br>
[EDIT?]   off  - on   [EDIT?]   the seemingly ludicrous idea of using nuclear bombs to propel a ship. ORION used specially designed directional bombs to ionize propellant and push it back towards the ship. The ship would carry a large plate, known as the pusher, with which to catch the propellant. Shock absorbers would reduce the force felt by the crew to survivable levels. The use of high energy nuclear fuel gave the system a high Isp, while the tremendous force generated by the bomb's plasma produced high thrust. Most propulsion systems offer high thrust, like a chemical rocket, or high Isp, like an ion thruster, but not both at the same time. This was one of the many advantages of ORION.<br>
<br>
What both groups realized was that chemical propulsion was not the path to opening up interplanetary travel. Nuclear fuel contains a million times the energy of chemical fuels. Even the best chemical propellants can only muster an Isp of 700s, with the reliable, common hydrogen-oxygen reaction mustering only 560s. The nuclear rockets of the NERVA program exceeded 900s, while even the watered down nuclear pulse drive desired by NASA produced an Isp of nearly 2000s in its smallest    <br>
<br>
[EDIT]   &quot;from&quot; - form   [EDIT]   . On interplanetary expeditions, greater efficiency means more room for payload, or much shorter transit times. von Braun's plan in his The Exploration of Mars called for a transit of 260 days to get from Earth to Mars (5). The fastest ORION transits in the NASA study were only 60 days.<br>
<br>
EMPIRE's Foundation<br>
<br>
 In May 1962, the George C. Marshall Space Flight Center selected three contactors to undertake independent 6 month, 6000 man-hour studies. The contractors were the Aeronutronic Division of Ford Motor Company, Lockheed Missiles and Space Company, and General Dynamics/Astronautics. The ground rules were simple: The total mission duration could not exceed 18 months; nuclear propulsion was to be used as the primary means of injection and breaking; the crew was to be completely integrated into vehicular systems; the studies had to take into account lessons form the early manned space program, integrating Apollo hardware when possible, including the Saturn-V HLV. They were to investigate Mars and Venus flybys, reconnaissance, and eventually a Mars landing.<br>
<br>
Aeronutronic produced their study in two reports; 'EMPIRE, A Study of Early Manned Interplanetary Missions' by M. H. Caldwell and ' The EMPIRE- Duel Planet Flyby Mission' by Franklin P. Dixon. Subsystem<br>
 Mass (kg)<br>
  <br>
As the studies suggest, Aeronutronic focused on a Venus/Mars flyby instead of a manned landing. At the time, many planners considered manned flyby missions. This was in part due to the unreliability of robotic probes of the era, and was seen by many in NASA as the logical first step before a landing(6). The mission of most interest was to follow a symmetrical orbit which would pass by both Venus and Mars. They planned to launch the mission from a 300 km orbit in July of 1970. The mission was to take a total of 21 months, leading Aeronutronic to provide artificial gravity for the nominal crew of six. Interplanetary flight also required a radiation shelter to protect the crew from solar flares. <br>
<br>
The ship consisted of two major parts: an injection stage containing a solid core nuclear rocket capable of 200000 lbs of thrust for 800 seconds. This motor would be fueled by two sets of external fuel tanks. The first set would be used for initial insertion into the trajectory, the second for a secondary burn. This first stage would then be discarded, although the second set of tanks would be retained as shielding for the flyby vehicle. Any additional maneuvers would be made by stored chemical rockets. The vehicle would deploy two crew living modules,   <br>
<br>
[EDIT]   totaling - totalling   [EDIT]   roughly 750 cubic feet per crewman, along telescoping arms on either side of the ship. A SNAP-8 reactor would be deployed to provide power, with a spare reactor in storage. By spinning the craft axially at 3 rpm, the ship would provide limited artificial gravity for the crew. This was desirable because the whole mission would be made in transit; 100 days from Earth to Venus, 200 days form Venus to Mars, and 310-340 days to return to Earth. The crew would reenter after a powered deceleration, leaving the ship to continue on to a solar orbit. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Lockheed had done several in-house studies related to Venus and Mars flybys before they received the contract for EMPIRE. Some of these focused on stopover trips; the ultimate focus of their EMPIRE study. Under the direction of Benjamin Martin, Lockheed planned flyby missions to Venus and Mars during the 1973-5 period, approaching within 500 nm of either world.<br>
<br>
Lockheed planned on keeping the total mass of the spacecraft to within the launch capability of two Saturn 5s. This put constraints on space and velocity. Lockheed saw four phases for the mission: heliocentric injection; mid-course correction; planetary approach; and orbital insertion for stop-over mission. Lockheed preferred to gradually step up from a flyby, to an orbiter, and finally to an actual landing (7). The mass constraint limited their designs to long transits, requiring a rotating ship to provide artificial gravity. Relying on Apollo architecture, they limited their crew to three. The craft consisted of three ridged 25 m spokes, tipped with a mission module, a command module, and the nuclear power system respectively. The central hub housed the midcourse propulsion unit and a solar shelter in one version. An alternative arrangement had the solar shelter combined with the command module.<br>
