 <br>
<br>
The mission module would house the crew's primary living space and life support. It was planned with a volume of 113 m^3, and would contain the food, water and spare parts necessary for the mission. The craft was to be launched in two portions and constructed in orbit. In the end, the standard Saturn 5 was incapable of launching the Mars flyby ship in two launches, although the Venus ship was within its capabilities. For this reason, Lockheed suggested that the Saturn 5/N be developed; the NERVA upper stage giving it improved performance (<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  . Even then, it would take three launches to put a satisfactory vehicle in orbit. Lockheed saw the Venus mission as lasting 370 days, while a Mars flyby had a 670 day cruise round trip.<br>
<br>
<br>
General Dynamics took an entirely different approach to their EMPIRE study. While Aeronutronic and Lockheed focused on slow flyby craft, General Dynamics envisioned ships with power. Rather than flyby missions with flight-times of roughly 650 days, they foresaw fast flybys and manned landings with total mission times of 450 days. They planned an expedition with nearly three times the crew of Lockheed, and 100 times the payload of Aeronutronic (9). Admittedly the Lockheed and Aeronutronic studies were meant as precursors, but General Dynamics followed in the bold footsteps of von Braun's visions of Mars, focusing primarily on the true capabilities of nuclear propulsion.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The General Dynamics team focused on two different vehicle configurations. The first involved having separate ships for the crew and destination equipment. This would limit the size of each ship to the 10 m diameter of the Saturn V. The vehicle's initial mass was a planned 434 tonnes. General Dynamics thought that total departure masses of 1200-1400 tonnes were more realistic vehicles capable of accomplishing Mars mission objectives best(10). For post-Saturn launch vehicles, a larger vehicle could be used, combining the mission hardware convoy vehicle with the crew vehicle. This allowed the crew access to hardware in-flight and would simplify the mission by not requiring an automated ship full of cargo. The Saturn V capable vehicle would use two Phoebus SCNRs, each producing 250000 lbs of thrust, in the M-1 stage, one Phoebes in the M-2 stage, and a NERVA engine producing 97000 lbs of thrust in the M-3 stage. The larger designs, such as the M-22 and M-23 used four Phoebus in the first stage, totaling 1000000 lbs of thrust.<br>
<br>
The crew total varied from as few as six to as many as sixteen, with eight being the preferred number (11). The crew module would house food, life support, and would even mount several space taxis for transferring from the crew vehicle to other vehicles in the convoy. The General Dynamics team believed that a convoy would maximize minimum energy launch windows, reducing flight times and safety should one ship suffer a malfunction (12).<br>
<br>
General Dynamics predicted that it would take eight Saturn Vs to place the desired vehicles in orbit. Like the other contractors, they supported the development of the post-Saturn HLV, usually referred to as the Nova, capable of lifting four times the mass to low Earth orbit (13). General Dynamics planned on carrying a vast assortment of vehicles to Mars as part of the 45400 kg destination payload, including rovers, mapping satellites, balloons, probes to study Mars' moons, as well as the decent and accent vehicles. The 450 day mission total involved a total of 180 days to Mars, 30 days for capture, and 240 days home. Artificial gravity would be produced by flipping the ship end over end. Easily the grandest of the EMPIRE plans, General Dynamics formulated a strategy which would become the standard for Mars missions into the 1980's. <br>
<br>
ORION's Finale<br>
<br>
ORION was born in 1958, although the idea had been played with for several years beforehand. Led by veteran bomb-designer Theodore Taylor and physicist Freeman Dyson, General Atomic had developed the project first under ARPA, and then the Air Force. NASA had clearly expressed it had no desire to take over the project, despite its focus on peaceful space flight. Many within NASA who learned about the project were more then a bit curious, including von Braun (14). Eventually NASA leadership was convinced to pay for a paper study in 1963. <br>
NASA's vision of ORION was very different from those previously considered by the General Atomic team. Rather then massive 4000-10000 ton ground launched vehicles shaped like a thimble, the ships in NASA's study were to be launched at least into the upper atmosphere, with orbital start-up preferred(15). Because of the size limitations of existing and planned chemical boosters, NASA wanted studies done on two sizes, a 10 m and 20 m diameter ships, at least half the size of the 40 m designs previously considered. The majority of the study was to focus on the smaller design as it was capable of being launched by the Saturn V, the larger 20 m would have required the proposed post-Saturn HLV. <br>
<br>
 <br>
Nuclear pulse rockets actually get more efficient as they increase in size. This meant that NASA's nuclear pulse vehicles represented the bottom limit of efficiency for the technology. Rather then 40 m ships with Isp's of 10000s, the 20 m could only muster 3150s, while the 10 m a paltry 1850s. The General Atomic team believed that advances in the next twenty years would more then double these Isp figures, making the smaller vehicles more capable. The designs were intended to   <br>
